snippet.textDisplay: That initial flight was almost completely empty - it had no WEIGHT. If it had a full complement of passengers, luggage and cargo, it would have weighed significantly more, and with more weight comes more inertia - the ability of an object in motion to continue in that motion. Added inertia will offer resistance to the plane being pushed around by wind.

snippet.textDisplay:
Citizens of St. Helena are NOT British citizens at all. They are part of  British Overseas Territories. Individuals with this nationality are British nationals and Commonwealth citizens, but not British citizens. The status itself does not grant right of abode in the United Kingdom or any of the territories. Nationals of this class are subject to immigration controls when entering the United Kingdom and do not have the automatic right to live or work there.

This is not like US territories (Guam, Puerto Rico, Virgin Island Marianna Island or who are US citizens or US nationals in case of the American Samoa who enjoy a full right to work and live in the US and convert to US citizenship any time.

The status itself does not grant right of abode in the United Kingdom or any of the territories. Nationals of this class are subject to immigration controls when entering the United Kingdom and do not have the automatic right to live or work there.

This is not like US territories (Guam, Puerto Rico, Virgin Island Marianna Island or who are US citizens or US nationals in case of the American Samoa who enjoy a full right to work and live in the US and convert to US citizenship any time.

snippet.textDisplay:
At one point in the interview of Gwenyth Howell (the CEO of St. Helena Airport LTD), she said...


..."They started the first construction - or the first moving of soil - in November 2011. And, obviously, they built various roads up to the airport because they had to get the logistics up to the airport. That was they had a ship that brought in all the materials, logistics, all the spares and the equipment that had to obviously help to build an airport."



I, obviously do NOT "know" this woman, but after listening to just that few seconds of her discussing the evolution of getting the charter/money to build the airport, then briefly reciting the bare bones basics of the general history of how it came about, I found myself wondering how in the world she qualified as the CEO of not only the St. Helena Airport LTD, but the CEO of ANYthing (i.e. even the ACME Sandbox Co.)! What sparked that thinking was the apparently very 'sketchy' use of the English language into coherent sentences, and the incorrect fashion in which she used the word "logistics" (at least TWICE), indicating that she seems to think that "logistics" are akin to physical objects, that you can pack in boxes and carry/transport to where they are needed. (HINT: They are NOT.) Considering her lack of understanding about something as basic as what "logistics" are, and their importance in getting something done, the fact that this airport actually got built with her in a high-level position of authority/oversight is nothing short of amazing! I just hope, for the good of the St. Helena citizenry, that the airport doesn't have to be rebuilt after ten years or so.



The definition of logistics is as follows:



"The process of planning, implementing, and controlling the efficient, effective flow and storage of goods, services and related information from their point of origin to point of consumption for the purpose of satisfying customer requirements."



As you can see, logistics are not "physical things" which can be box, transported.

snippet.textDisplay:
Seems like it might've been better-spent money to just relocate the several thousand people from the extremely-remote, very rugged island that needs financial aid just to exist as a settlement (getting ~twice as much money as its tax revenue). The 'saving lives' aspect of the airport wouldn't be needed if they didn't live in the middle of nowhere in the first place.
285 million pounds for the airport, island population of 4,500. That's about 60,000 pounds per person for the airport, and another 5,000 pounds per person per year given to the island by the U.K., year after year. We don't HAVE to keep the island populated, and getting there for things like tourism is a huge waste of resources.

snippet.textDisplay:
I know it as my cousins and uncle lived there for several years. My uncle was Paul Blessington- he was the financial secretary (in other words the Chancellor of The Exchequer) for St Helena and he main project was the airport. His signature was on St Helena’s £5 and £10 pound note. Devastatingly Paul died at the age of in 2012 by cancer after being taken in suddenly to Cape Town by RMS St Helena with a Nurse while his wife travelled there by a Cargo ship. He was a seriously fit man who enjoyed long running journeys and challenges like achieving the fastest time on Jacob’s Ladder (which he still has today). He was always great personality and we all dearly miss him.

I bet he took the role of financial secretary to heart and did the best he could for the island. He never saw his project fulfilled. Paul always inspired me to challenge myself and put 110% into life; that’s why I hope one day we’ll be able visit St Helena as a family to say one last proper goodbye to him.

I find it a shame that RMS St Helena doesn’t carry on for tourists who want to view St Helena from the sea not the sky. It would be favourable for retired tourists and tourist families. Both would be useful for St Helena’s economy.

snippet.textDisplay:
I always thought that the name of the island was pronounced Saint 'HEL-en-uh' rather than Saint 'huh-LEEN-uh'... But, the locals in this film seem to use the latter pronunciation, so I suppose I'll have to take their (literal) word for it...

But, doesn't the etymology of the name come from saint Helen (Which would argue for the former pronunciation, I think)...? I guess I'll listen to the locals, though, if I ever make it there (It's fairly high up on my list of places to see, along with Antarctica and the Falklands, and now, apparently, I can fly there more easily!)... I'll probably embarrass myself vis-a-vis the pronunciation, either way: I tend to do that, generally speaking. Oh well...

Cool vid, BTW... Keep 'em coming! (+1).
